{"source_key":"sha256-8059706feeaf84eb5ef46af56e37af05","record_index":13,"record_hash":"sha256:c25c5f1ba0181dc1f6b4715fb7e81a54ee444932c0104f2194df14c382307f4b","timestamp":"2026-06-19T09:38:54.786Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 01869d\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 792\nOutput:\n---\nname: brainstorming\ndescription: Use before creative implementation work—creating features, building components, adding functionality, or modifying behavior—when you need to explore intent, requirements, constraints, and design before touching code. For this workspace, adapt the flow to OpenClaw and local planning artifacts rather than OpenCode-specific tools.\n---\n\n# Brainstorming\n\nTurn ideas into clear designs and approved specs through collaborative dialogue.\n\n## Hard gate\n\nDo not implement, scaffold, write code, or invoke coding/execution skills until:\n1. you have explored the current project context,\n2. asked clarifying questions as needed,\n3. proposed approaches with tradeoffs,\n4. presented a design, and\n5. the user has approved the design.\n\nEven simple work gets a design pass. The design can be short when the task is small, but it still needs to exist.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Explore project context first\n   - Read relevant files, docs, and recent repo state.\n   - Follow existing patterns before proposing change.\n2. Ask clarifying questions one at a time\n   - Prefer multiple choice when helpful.\n   - Focus on purpose, constraints, success criteria, and scope.\n3. Propose 2–3 approaches\n   - Include tradeoffs.\n   - Lead with your recommendation and why.\n4. Present the design\n   - Scale detail to complexity.\n   - Cover architecture, components, data flow, failure modes, and testing where relevant.\n   - Confirm it looks right before moving on.\n5. Write the design down\n   - Save to `docs/superpowers/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>-design.md` unless the repo already has a better local convention.\n6. Self-review the written design\n   - Remove placeholders.\n   - Fix contradictions.\n   - Tighten ambiguity.\n   - Ensure the scope is appropriate for one implementation plan.\n7. Ask the user to review the spec file\n   - Wait for approval or edits.\n8. Transition to planning\n   - Use the `writing-plans` skill next.\n\n## Scope discipline\n\nIf the request actually describes multiple independent subsystems, stop and decompose it first. Create a spec for the first sub-project instead of pretending one giant spec will stay coherent.\n\n## Design guidance\n\n- Break systems into units with one clear purpose.\n- Prefer clear interfaces and well-bounded files/modules.\n- Stay focused on improvements that serve the current goal.\n- In existing codebases, match local conventions unless a targeted cleanup is part of the design.\n- Be ruthless about YAGNI.\n\n## Visual companion note\n\nThe upstream version references a browser-based visual companion. In OpenClaw, use available visualization or browser tooling only when the environment actually supports it and when visuals would materially improve understanding. Do not assume a browser companion exists.\n\n## Output expectations\n\nWhen the design is approved, write a concise but durable spec that another agent can use without relying on chat memory.\n\nSuggested review message:\n\n> Spec written to `<path>`. Please review it and tell me if you want any changes before I write the implementation plan.\n\n## Transition\n\nAfter the spec is approved, invoke `writing-plans`. Do not skip directly into implementation.","tool_name":"exec_command","tool_kind":"exec","tool_input":null,"exit_code":0,"outcome":"succeeded","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-19T09:38:54.786Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}